2.) Make a plot of total CO2 emissions over time for the U.S, China, and India. Add a few more countries of your choice. Explain what do you see.

Based on the graph, it appears that China and India have had increasing CO2 emissions since the year 2000, which could reflect increased industrialization and overall economic activity in that time. In contrast, the United States has slightly decreased its emissions since 2000, which could reflect changing attitudes on what energy sources should be used, both for production and other means. As expected, the two European countries have much lower emissions, which most probably indicates their use of alternative energy sources and lack of dependence on fossil fuels.

3.) Now let’s analyze the CO2 emissions per capita (co2_PC ). Make a similar plot of the same countries. What does this figure suggest?

In some ways, this graph suggests similar things as the previous, since we see some of the same trends. For instance, we still see the general trend
that India & China have increased emissions recently while the
U.S. has decreased. The main difference in this graph is that, for the European countries, we can see how emissions has either grown or decreased as a proportion of their population size. Because the trend lines are fairly close to the other countries in terms of CO2 per capita, we can infer that total CO2 emissions are largely a function of population size.

GDP per capita

1.) Make a scatterplot of GDP per capita versus life expectancy by country, using data for 1960. Make the point size dependent on the country size, and color those according to the continent. Feel free to adjust the plot in other ways to make it better.

2.) Make a similar plot, but this time use 2019 data only.

3.) Compare these two plots and comment what do you see. How has world developed through the last 60 years?

From both of the plots, we can see that as you raise GDP to a sufficiently high level, life expectancy increases along with it. However, the major difference between the two plots is the scales. For the 1960 plot, life expectancy went up to only 70 while GDP per capita went up to 20000. IN contrast, for the 2019 plot, life expectancy went up to 80 and GDP per capita went up to 90000. This tells us that both GDP per capita AND life expectancy have increased drastically throughout the world since the beginning of the dataset.
